DBSCAN is one of the most effective clustering algorithms. It is robust against noise and works well with given data. It is this algorithm that is most recommended for use. It is recommended to use in two dimensions with an Epsilon parameter equal to 50%
Epsilon: determines the radius near the point, represented not as an absolute value, but as a percentage, and 50% is the optimal value calculated by the algorithm
Minimum number of points in a cluster: the minimum number of points in one cluster, an integer

Gaussian Mixture is a complex probabilistic clustering algorithm. It is not recommended to use with a dimension greater than two due to high costs of clustering. When used with a larger dimension, clustering will take much longer.
Number of clusters: number of created clusters
K-means is one of the simplest clustering algorithms. It works very fast, so it can be used for large data sets.
Number of clusters: the number of clusters that will be created during clustering
Seed: so that the same algorithms give different output data

The developed web application enables flexible use and choice of clustering algorithms. Four main types of clustering algorithms are implemented: k-means, DBSCAN, Gaussian Mixture and Spectral Clustering. Another additional One Cluster algorithm was also implemented, although it cannot be called a full-fledged clustering algorithm. These are only types of algorithms, not specific implementations. The user himself creates a specific implementation of the algorithm with specific properties individual for each algorithm.

Demonstration of work on the example of the k-means algorithm. The user must first create a specific algorithm. To do this, he opens the page of adding algorithms, selects k-means. In this case, k-means has two properties: the number of clusters and the seed. The user enters the properties he needs and creates an algorithm. After that, it is possible to use the clustering algorithm. This particular algorithm is used with specific properties specified by the user. Such a system allows you to create algorithms for specific cases of clustering, which improves the final result.

One cluster is the simplest clustering algorithm. It does not perform analysis functions, but only groups all points into one cluster. This is done for convenient visualization of data without breaking the logic of interaction.
Spectral Clustering is an algorithm that is too complex from the point of view of calculations, so its use is not recommended due to too complex calculations and time consumption.

Creating embeddings or vector visualization of text is the process of converting text data into an array of numbers. The first transformation models worked like dictionaries, they took a large number of words. However, if a word was found in the dictionary, the number of such words in the text was placed on it. As a result, we received an array of numbers that relatively represented the text. This technology is quite primitive, and could not work with synonyms or larger language structures. Today, much better models based on artificial intelligence are used, which help to convert text into an array of numbers much better. The web application uses the text-embedding-ada-002 model from OpenAI. In this case, the text is converted into a 1536-dimensional array (that is, 1536 numbers).

This application was created to automate the clustering of text data. This means complete automation, including preparation processes and loading of text data for clustering. The user downloads text data (for example, comments from the YouTube, and this happens without leaving this site) and performs flexible clustering with many parameters.

Cluster analysis is the task of dividing a given sample of objects (situations) into subsets, called clusters, so that each cluster consists of similar objects, and the objects of different clusters differ significantly. The task of clustering belongs to statistical processing, as well as to a broad class of unsupervised learning tasks. In the case of comments from the YouTube platform, cluster analysis helps to group objects actually by meaning.

Text clustering can be conventionally divided into four stages: loading of text data, creation of embeddings (or vector clustering of text), reduction of data dimensionality and, accordingly, clustering.

In the developed web application, downloading text data can be done in two ways: downloading comments from the YouTube platform (using the capabilities of the web application) or downloading external sources in a special format.

Loading ebmedings or vector representation of text is the process of converting text into an array of numbers (vector). The application interacts with the text-embedding-ada-002 model from the OpenAi company.
For a normal display of the original clusters, it is necessary to reduce the dimension of the array of numbers. This is done using different dimensionality reduction algorithms.

Four main types of algorithms are used during clustering: DBSCAN, K-means, Spectral Clustering and Gaussian Mixture. By choosing a type, the user himself creates a specific algorithm with certain properties, so the number of real implementations of algorithms is actually unlimited.
All stages and subtleties are described in detail in the relevant sections.

Dynamic loading of points on the map is implemented for better performance. Each point map consists of levels, which in turn are divided into squares. This approach is used by online maps (for example, Google maps). For non-hierarchical clustering, only one level is created, which is divided 16 by 16, creating 256 equal squares. When viewing, only those squares that the user sees are downloaded. So there is no need to download all the points, which increases performance with a large amount of data.

The point map is responsible for displaying the final clusters. Each profile has its own map of points, and it becomes available after the first clustering of the profile. Each point is responsible for its own text (comment or text from external data). Points of the same color belong to the same cluster. Points are loaded dynamically.
By clicking on a specific point, its content is highlighted.

The quota system is implemented to ensure the safety of the application from overloading due to loading and processing an infinite amount of data. Each registered user (who has verified his email address) has certain restrictions on the use of some functions of the site. If the limit is exceeded, the user will not be able to use the corresponding function, but additional quotas can be obtained from the administration. A quota purchase system is also under development

The first package of quotas is issued once after passing mail verification, each action (for which quotas are taken) costs a different number of them. Also, there are different types of quotas and the corresponding amount available for each type. Even if the user has used all quotas of one type, other actions with the application that are not related to this type of quotas will not be affected in any way. When initializing an action that requires a quota, the user will in most cases be informed about the possible number of used quotas. But not all actions directly display a warning about the number of quotas, so it is recommended to read the relevant section on the price of quotas for each operation

The provision of quotas to the user is not done directly, but with the help of quota packs. Each pack contains a certain number of quotas of each type, which are credited to the user when the pack is activated
The first pack is provided upon email verification. Also, the user can see a list of all activated packs on the corresponding account page
